<node id="bletchley_park">
  <data key="d0">Bletchley Park</data>
  <data key="d1">Organization</data>
  <data key="d2">Bletchley Park is an English country house and estate in Bletchley, Milton Keynes (Buckinghamshire), that became the principal centre of Allied code-breaking during the Second World War. During World War II, the estate housed the Government Code and Cypher School (GC&amp;CS), which regularly penetrated the secret communications of the Axis powers – most importantly the German Enigma and Lorenz ciphers. The GC&amp;CS team of codebreakers included John Tiltman, Dilwyn Knox, Alan Turing, Harry Golombek, Gordon Welchman, Hugh Alexander, Donald Michie, Bill Tutte and Stuart Milner-Barry.</data>
  <data key="d3">wikipedia</data>
  <data key="d4">[{"value": "Station X", "datatype": "string", "source": "wikidata", "confidence": "0.95"}]</data>
  <data key="d5">[{"value": "1877", "datatype": "gYear", "source": "wikidata", "confidence": "0.90"}]</data>
